  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This process is intended to obscure the origins of the money and make it appear as though it comes from legitimate sources.\n\nMoney laundering is typically associated with activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, corruption, and other forms of organized crime. The legal frameworks to combat money laundering are part of broader efforts to prevent and prosecute financial crimes, and they often involve stringent regulations and international cooperation.\n\nIn many countries, the laws related to money laundering are robust, and the penalties can be severe, including substantial fines and lengthy prison sentences. Financial institutions and certain businesses are also required to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities that might be indicative of money laundering.",
